alloca

    Usage

	#include <stdlib.h>
	void __ss *alloca(size_t size);

    Description

	alloca() provides an efficient way to allocate a
	temporary amount of storage within the current
	stack frame. No corresponding free function is
	necessary, since the stack frame is discarded when
	the function returns. This means that a pointer to
	an alloca'd buffer cannot be returned from a function.

	alloca() is implemented as a compiler intrinsic,
	that is, the compiler recognizes it and performs
	special action to support it. This means that you
	should never define your own alloca function. It also
	means that alloca() is reliable.

	alloca() cannot be used in functions that have the
	Windows prolog/epilog in them, i.e. functions compiled
	with the -W flag.

    Example

    Return Value

	Returns NULL if an error occurred. Otherwise, returns
	a pointer into the current stack frame of the allocated
	data.

	Although a stack-relative pointer is returned, this is
	usually implicitly cast by the compiler into the correct
	pointer type.

    See Also

	malloc, free

    Compatibility

	alloca() works across all Zortech implementations. It,
	however, is not an ANSI C function. The implementation
	quality of it varies considerably from compiler to
	compiler, and is not even implemented by many compilers.
