_beginthread

    Usage

	#include <process.h>
	int _beginthread(void (_far *thread_func)(void _far *),
		void _far *stack_buf, unsigned stack_size,
		void _far *argument);

    Description

	Starts execution of a new thread starting at the
	function thread_func. stack_buf is the address of
	a memory buffer to be used as a stack by the thread.
	stack_buf must be word aligned for 16 bit compiles,
	and dword aligned for 32 bit compiles.
	stack_size gives the size of that buffer, at least
	2048 bytes. If stack_buf is NULL, the _beginthread()
	will malloc a buffer for the stack.

	argument is a 32 bit value to be passed to thread_func.
	It is usually a pointer to the data that the thread function
	is to operate on.

	The thread is terminated by a call to _endthread() within
	thread_func, or by the return from thread_func. A thread
	created by _beginthread() must not be terminated by
	a call to the OS/2 function DosExit().

	It is necessary to use _beginthread()/_endthread() to start
	and end threads whenever those threads will call routines
	in the runtime library. These functions ensure that the
	library routines are properly synchronized.

    Example

    Return Value

	If successful, returns the thread id of the created thread.
	Otherwise, -1 is returned and errno is set.

    See Also

	_endthread

    Compatibility

	Multithreaded programming is currently only supported
	under OS/2.
-----------------------------------
_endthread

    Usage

	#include <process.h>
	void _endthread(void);

    Description

	Terminates execution of a thread that was started
	by _beginthread().

    Example

    Return Value

	None.

    See Also

	_beginthread

    Compatibility

	Multithreaded programming is currently only supported
	under OS/2.
-----------------------------------
_msize

    Usage

	#include <stdlib.h>
	size_t _msize(void *p);

    Description

	Returns actual size of a block of memory allocated
	by malloc/calloc/realloc.
	This is implemented as a macro.

    Example

    Return Value

	Size in bytes of block of memory.

    See Also

	malloc, calloc, realloc

    Compatibility

	ANSI		-
	DOS		x
	ZPM		x
	DOS16RM		x
	DOS386		x
	Pharlap 386	x
	OS/2 1.x	x
	SCO Unix 386	-
	Windows 3.0	x
	Macintosh	-
